# Complaint to Determine Dischargeability of Debt

Produces a court-ready adversary complaint seeking a determination that a specified debt is excepted from discharge.

## Prerequisites

1. Bankruptcy case metadata: court, district, chapter, main case number, petition date, § 341(a) meeting date, Rule 4007(c) deadline.
2. Parties data: full legal names, addresses, entity type, aliases, and relationship to the debt.
3. Debt record: contract/loan docs, invoices, payment history, communications, admissions, and damage calculation.
4. Chosen § 523 subsection(s) and controlling circuit elements.
5. Chronology of key events with dates, amounts, and participants.
6. Evidence list mapped to each element (documents, witnesses, admissions).
7. Local bankruptcy rules for caption, line numbering, service, and ECF signature format.

## Output Structure / Process

| Section | Required content |
| --- | --- |
| Caption | U.S. Bankruptcy Court, district, main case no., adversary no. blank, parties, title. |
| Jurisdiction/Venue | 28 U.S.C. §§ 1334, 157; core proceeding § 157(b)(2)(I); venue § 1409. |
| Parties | Standing, chain of title if assignee/subrogee; debtor identifiers and chapter. |
| General Allegations | Numbered paragraphs; chronological facts; evidence anchors. |
| Counts | Separate counts per § 523 subsection with element-by-element facts. |
| Prayer | Nondischargeability judgment; amount breakdown; costs; fees if authorized; interest; other relief. |
| Signature | Attorney block with bar info; ECF signature per local rule. |
| Verification | Include only if required by local rule or court order. |

Jurisdiction/Venue/Timeliness checklist:
- [ ] § 1334 subject-matter jurisdiction alleged.
- [ ] § 157 reference and core proceeding § 157(b)(2)(I) alleged.
- [ ] § 1409 venue alleged.
- [ ] Petition date and § 341(a) meeting date stated.
- [ ] Rule 4007(c) timeliness alleged for § 523(a)(2), (4), (6).

Fraud pleading (Rule 9(b) via Rule 7009) checklist:
- [ ] Who made the statement or omission.
- [ ] What was said or concealed.
- [ ] When and where it occurred.
- [ ] How it was false or misleading.
- [ ] Knowledge of falsity and intent to deceive.
- [ ] Reliance and why it was justifiable.
- [ ] Causation and damages with amounts.

Elements mapping table (tailor to circuit law):

| § 523 theory | Elements to plead | Required factual allegations |
| --- | --- | --- |
| § 523(a)(2)(A) | Misrepresentation/false pretenses/actual fraud; intent; justifiable reliance; proximate loss | Specific statements or omissions, intent facts, reliance behavior, loss calculation. |
| § 523(a)(2)(B) | Written statement respecting financial condition; materially false; intent to deceive; reasonable reliance | Exact document, falsity, reliance details, damages link. |
| § 523(a)(4) | Fiduciary capacity or embezzlement/larceny; defalcation or fraud | Existence of express trust or fiduciary duty, breach, misappropriation, accounting failures. |
| § 523(a)(6) | Willful and malicious injury | Intent to injure or substantial certainty of harm; malicious conduct; injury specifics. |

Count template:
```text
COUNT __: NONDISCHARGEABILITY UNDER 11 U.S.C. § 523(____)
1. Plaintiff realleges paragraphs __ through __.
2. Element 1: [state element]. Facts: [cite numbered paragraphs].
3. Element 2: [state element]. Facts: [cite numbered paragraphs].
4. Element 3: [state element]. Facts: [cite numbered paragraphs].
5. As a result, the debt of $[amount] is excepted from discharge under § 523(____).
```

Authorities to cite (as applicable):
- 11 U.S.C. § 523.
- 28 U.S.C. §§ 1334, 157, 157(b)(2)(I), 1409.
- Fed. R. Bankr. P. 7001, 7009, 7012, 4007(c), 9011.
- Fraud reliance standard: Field v. Mans [VERIFY].
- Actual fraud scope: Husky Int’l Elecs., Inc. v. Ritz [VERIFY].
- Willful and malicious injury: Kawaauhau v. Geiger [VERIFY].

Prayer for relief checklist:
- [ ] Declaration of nondischargeability for specified debt.
- [ ] Judgment amount itemized by principal, interest, fees, costs.
- [ ] Prejudgment/post-judgment interest (statutory or contractual).
- [ ] Attorney’s fees if contract or statute permits.
- [ ] Other just and proper relief.

## Guidelines

- Plead only facts with evidentiary support or likely support after investigation (Rule 9011).
- Use numbered paragraphs throughout; avoid conclusory element recitations.
- Align each count to controlling circuit elements and terminology.
- Avoid inconsistent theories unless pled as alternatives and factually supportable.
- Maintain professional tone; no inflammatory rhetoric.
- Confirm Rule 4007(c) deadline compliance for § 523(a)(2), (4), (6).
- Follow local bankruptcy court formatting, line numbering, and ECF signature rules.
- Attach exhibits only when required or strategically necessary; otherwise identify and reference them clearly.
